      "text": "audit rules.d\n\nRules are locked with the `e -2` flag, this can be\nremoved but requires a reboot to take affect, so\nthere isn't much point. It's better to just copy the\nnew rules into rules.d path, then they are loaded at\nboot, with the lock still applied.\n\nDeleting the directory before copying the new rules\nensures that we don't have rules being loaded in the\nwrong order. Rules work in a first match basis, if\nthe broad rules are loaded before the specific, you\ncan miss audit logs. We have named the rules with\nnumbered prefixes to avoid this issue.\n\n    augenrules --load  | load rules\n    augenrules --check | check rules\n    auditctl -l        | list loaded rules\n    auditctl -s        | show settings",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": "cCJjkg7SB-1ABpCGMdx0k",
      "originalText": "audit rules.d\n\nRules are locked with the `e -2` flag, this can be removed but requires a reboot to take affect, so there isn't much point. It's better to just copy the new rules into rules.d path, then they are loaded at boot, with the lock still applied.\n\nDeleting the directory before copying the new rules ensures that we don't have rules being loaded in the wrong order. Rules work in a first match basis, if the broad rules are loaded before the specific, you can miss audit logs. We have named the rules with numbered prefixes to avoid this issue.\n\n    augenrules --load  | load rules\n    augenrules --check | check rules\n    auditctl -l        | list loaded rules\n    auditctl -s        | show settings",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
